{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500463"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:14:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:14:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1649"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1649"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.4,0.22,0.01,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1649"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106771"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1649"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1649"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89251"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"880"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2947"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2968"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35161"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42360"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106771"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old Caucasian man presents to his GP with the following lesion on his back after his friend noticed it while at the beach (Image). He is unsure when the lesion first appeared. He denies any previous history of skin lesions or malignancy. He does not take any regular medications and denies having any allergies. He denies a known family history of melanoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well and his vitals are within normal limits. His skin is a Fitzpatrick phototype III.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Superficial spreading melanoma","Halo naevus","Dysplastic naevus","Lichen sclerosus","Lentigo maligna melanoma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehalo naevus\u003C/strong\u003E. It is characterised by a sharp region of depigmentation surrounding the centrally pigmented naevus. This appearance is attributed to an autoimmune reaction to a naevus. Their appearance frequently leads to confusion with \u003Cstrong\u003Emelanoma\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThey most commonly present in older children and young adults, and rarely present over the age of 30. They are most commonly noticed during the summer months in Caucasians as the depigmented skin will not tan. Halo naevi may be associated with vitiligo and other autoimmune diseases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe lesions may develop anywhere on the body but most commonly affect the truncal region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHalo naevi are benign and no treatment is required; the central naevus will gradually regress over several months. Dermoscopy may be used to further evaluate the naevus. If melanoma is suspected, then an excisional biopsy is recommended. Features that should increase suspicion include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA solitary lesion with an irregular area of depigmentation surrounding a naevus which is asymmetrical, has irregular borders or colour variation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA new halo naevus in an older patient\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Edysplastic or atypical naevus\u003C/strong\u003E is a mole with unusual features and must have at least 3 of the following:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESize \u0026gt;5mm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIrregular borders\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIrregular shape\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVariation in colour\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFlat and raised components\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt does not have the classic depigmented area as seen in halo naevi.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELichen sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic skin condition that presents as white crinkled or thickened patches of skin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Halo naevus is a benign lesion with a depigmented halo surrounding a pigmented central naevus"],"references":["Weyant GW, Chung CG, Helm KF. Halo nevus: review of the literature and clinicopathologic findings. Int J Dermatol. 2015;54(10):e433-5."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89251"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1649"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1616"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1616"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/84ca010c-e754-401e-88e3-29900c4b166f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/84ca010c-e754-401e-88e3-29900c4b166f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":752,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89251"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-22T14:18:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-23T14:15:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1649"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id